      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Goblins eating your profit\" is just a way of saying that if you don't keep your paperwork and contracts absolutely tight, those little, sneaky problems—the delays, the wrong documentation, the claims that get lost in the bureaucracy—they sneak in and chew up your money! It's like a horde of tiny, hungry goblins swarming your ledger, nibbling away at your margins until you're left with nothing but dust and regret.\n\nThese little things are the real thieves in trade, much worse than any actual sea monster. They don't smash things; they just slowly, methodically erode your earnings. I saw a shipment of fine silks get delayed because the customs declaration had a misplaced digit—a tiny error, but it cost the buyer a fortune in demurrage fees. It was like a goblin sneaking into the warehouse and just *taking* the value, one tiny piece at a time.\n\nSo, when I say keep the paperwork tight, I mean make sure every single clause is solid, like reinforcing a weak wall against a goblin raid. You want to make sure the liability lines are drawn clearly, or those little gremlins will find a gap to slip through and steal your hard-earned coin",
